        "text": "A story map[http://jpattonassociates.com/the-new-backlog/ The new user story backlog is a map] is a graphical, two-dimensional visualization of the product backlog ([[Product Backlog]]). At the top of the map are the headings under which stories are grouped, usually referred to as 'epics' (big coarse-grained user stories[http://www.romanpichler.com/blog/10-tips-writing-good-user-stories/ 10 Tips for Writing Good User Stories]), 'themes' (collections of related user stories[http://www.mountaingoatsoftware.com/blog/stories-epics-and-themes/ User Stories, Epics and Themes]) or 'activities'. These are identified by orienting at the user’s workflow or \"the order you'd explain the behavior of the system\". Vertically, below the epics, the actual story cards are allocated and ordered by priority. The first horizontal row is a \"walking skeleton\"[http://alistair.cockburn.us/Walking+skeleton Walking Skeleton]  and below that represents increasing sophistication.[https://www.agilealliance.org/glossary/storymap/ Story Mapping] - [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_Story#Story_map wikipedia]"
